Facebook (FB ‚Äì O): Helfstein

For Second Time, Mgmt Refocuses On Social vs. Media Content; Pricing Still Has Upside

Last night in a Facebook post, CEO Mark Zuckerberg said the company would

change the newsfeed algorithm to prioritize Social content (posted by Friends) above

Publisher content. Recall, this is the second time that mgmt raised concerns that

Social content was being overwhelmed by Media content‚Äîduring the first episode,

mgmt was worried that engagement would fall as users were posting less Social

content‚Äîwhen in fact, the opposite happened. As such, mgmt is now saying that

engagement would likely fall as a result of these changes. The obvious take-away is

that ad volume is likely to come under pressure, as mgmt has talked about holding

ad yield constant. Meanwhile, revenue has been disproportionately driven by pricing

(+15%, +24% and +35% in 1Q, 2Q and 3Q y/y, respectively). Our calculation of

FB's US revenue/hour is still trailing GOOG and TWTR's, suggesting potential further

pricing gains are possible, in part, driven by Instagram, which trails FB in ad load, and

by the maturation of the video ad product (perhaps similar to GOOG‚Äôs Trueview ads,

where users are forced to watch 5 seconds before they can skip the ad). This also

gives FB a way to remove some of the ‚Äúfake news‚Äù content that has become a risk

for the company long-term. While investors will likely have to wait until earnings on

Jan. 31 for a formal update, we would use weakness as a buying opportunity as this

‚Äúevent‚Äù shows us how powerful and important a platform FB has become for users.

We are still willing the play the long-term monetization upside.

Most startup employees go to another startup after getting bought out. It's a very common industry trend. That's why they often get ridiculous packages to stay, but it often does not matter. It changes a bit if GOOG or FB buys them out since it looks good on the resume to stay. WMT needs to pay about 50&#37; higher than GOOG and FB to get the top talent to stay. A company like ADSK has to pay 25&#37; more to get the top talent to stay because it's not as well known, yet it has a good rep. WMT has a bad rep. It looks really, really bad to have it on your resume. I would guess you need 50&#37; higher or so to get the best of the best in this case.

Actually back in the day there were negative dividends.  Stock is supposed to be owning a portion of a company, and to help raise money without selling more stock, some companies would issue negative dividends when they were loosing money.  In owning part of a company you profited when the company was profitable, and lost money while it wasn't (but in doing so you were helping support them through bad times so that they could turn around and make money).

While I am in the minority on this, I am all for going back to that.  We have so much bullshit today, like $GOOG = dividend-less class C stock with no voting rights.  Check its perspectus, what do you own? Oh nothing but it is redeemable for 1¬¢ (no seriously go check that out).  What is $GOOG trading for?  Oh that is right, your fucking penny is trading for $1,139 at the moment.  If negative dividends came back, stock prices would actually start reflecting reality again, and stock would actually be valuable for a company, propping them up in downtimes without forcing them to take on extra debt.

Before buying spreads(bad idea, I sell them and have only had two losers in 3 years), you really need to understand the risks associated with selling options. When you sell options, puts or calls, you‚Äôre selling an obligation to buy or sell stocks. In not like buying options, which give you the option to buy them or just let the option expire. 

For example, if you sell 5 naked calls of GOOG 2000 calls, you may be responsible for selling $1,000,000 of stock that you don‚Äôt own. Say the price is 2010 at expiration(or earlier if you get called) you would have to buy the stock for $2,100,000 and sell it for $2MM. You just lost $100k. 

Yes- I know this is an extreme example, but it can and has happened before. This is why most brokerages don‚Äôt let just anyone sell option. 

In fairness, spreads are a little different, but there is a lot or risk involved and you have to know what you‚Äôre doing.
